@Node INTRO

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

  Computers are in use every day throughout the world. Millions of
users switch on their machines every day to perform a variety of
different tasks.
 Some process some words. Others render the latest morphing effect for
the next blockbuster movie, control airport traffic systems or hold
details on criminals. A couple even play the latest version of Alien
Space Mutants from Mars.
  Once they have done whatever they wanted to do, most users switch
off their computers and go away. If they want to contact someone, they
will send them a letter or telephone them. If they want a new utility,
some clip - art or a game they will order them from a shop. These
people don't realise the potential their own machines have. With a
device called a modem they could make new friends and  talk to
thousands of other computer users around the world. Sure, they can
talk about computing, but not just that - they can chat about anything
- from the paranormal to  cookery to films.
   If they are after some software then using their computer, a modem
and terminal software they can obtain a program to do almost anything.
There are also text files available on any subject you can think of-
You could get hold of the complete lyrics of all your favourite songs
or obtain the complete works of Shakespeare whilst sitting in your
room.

Obviously YOU have seen the light!

If you are reading this then I presume that :

(1) You have an Amiga
(2) You have a modem or are at least interested in getting one

So what is this guide all about then? Well everyone who is new to comms
will come up against some sort of obstacle as they wade through the
various @{ " Bulletin Board Systems " link BBS} they call. Whether you are having
@{ " unarchiving " link ARCHIVERS} problems or you can't work out why your can't view that
@{ " text " link DOCS} file  you just got, I hope to explain. I will
also include other stuff such as how to calculate your @{ " phone bill " link COST}.

I intend to give you a general overview of some of the things you can do with
your modem, and look at some of the places you can visit from your desk.

I assume that you have an Amiga because I will be referring to some Amiga
specific stuff; and anyway the whole point of using Amigaguide is to
allow you to pick the topics that you are interested in and go straight
to them without hassle.

I hope this guide is of some use to someone! If you have any comments, I'd
love to hear from you- what have I missed, what would you like to see included
and what have I done wrong..? See @{ " Info " link INFO} for details of
contacting me.

Thanks

@{b}Paul Moore@{ub}

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@node ARCHIVERS

Once you have got a file onto your Amiga (If your software is set to
transfer it to memory, make sure you copy it onto a disk before you
reset your machine!) you will then wish to use it. You will notice that
most @{ " BBS " link BBS}files have a strange suffix on the end such as .lha or .lzh .
These files are archived. This means that they have been compressed so
they will take up a smaller amount of space and will not take as long
to download to your computer.

The most common Amiga archiving program is Lha. You will see variants of
this such as Lzh or Lz. I recommend getting hold of a copy of Lha as it
is probably the best archiver. You will find the latest version on your
local BBS in a form that does not require an archiver (self-extracting).
The program should contain documentation. Most unarchivers use the shell/
CLI but there are programs such as @{ " GUIarc " system "display commsguide.005"}  that can provide an easy to
use interface for programs.

@{b}Common Archive types@{ub}

So you will recognise them, here are some archive types you will meet.

.Lha - Requires Lha to unarchive.Most common on Amiga.
.Lz  - A variation on Lha
.Lzh - A variation on Lha
.ZIP - A common IBM PC format, but you will sometimes come across text
       files that are .ZIPped and so there are programs such as UNZIP
       and PKAzip on the Amiga that can deal with this format
.RUN
or
.SFX - An archive created with LhaSFX or similar. These types of archive
       are self-extracting and unarchive to the current directory when
       you double click them and press enter, or run them from shell.

.ARJ -  Another common PC format. There is an Amiga program called UnArj
        can extract files from these archives.

Other archive types you may come across are the older .ARC and .ZOO.
If you need to unpack a file in these formats you will find a program
on your favourite BBS to do this.


@endnode

