@NODE COST

The main disadvantage of using a modem is of course the cost. You have to
pay BT money every time you call, so it is quite easy to run up a HUGE phone
bill.

Here's how to calculate how much you just spent:

Generally,
                  Number of minutes online * 60
           Cost = -----------------------------  * 5
                  Number of seconds per unit

This will allow you to calculate fairly accurately the amount you spend on
a call. Calls cost 5p per BT unit at the moment (March 1994) and the number
of seconds per unit depends on what time of day it is.

Your phone bill will contain a booklet advising you of up-to date prices
and the number of seconds per unit.

I recommend phoning at the weekend as BT's new weekend rate means that calls
will cost the same wherever in the UK you are calling. You get 3 minutes for
10p at weekend rate.

Here is an example to illustrate the above:

e.g 12 mins at weekend rate = 90 secs per unit
    1 unit=5p

    =   12 * 60

    = 720
      --- *5
      90

    = 40p

Here are some general tips for cost-cutting:

* Make sure you buy the fastest modem you can afford. The slower the modem,
 the more time you spend online- believe me, I know :-)

* You can use your Comms software's capture facility to have a good look at
  the layout of a board and familiarize yourself with keyboard commands
  before your next call.

* @{ " archive " link ARCHIVERS} files. Files on a BBS will take a shorter
  time to @{ " upload/download " link PROTOCOLS} if they have been archived.

* Call only at cheap rate or weekend rate

* If you read lots of messages get some Offline Mail Reading software. Your
  Sysop will be able to help you set this up.

* Consider other phone companies. Mercury charges less for long distance
  calls.

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE LOGON

Once you have configured your @{ " software " link SOFTWARE} you will then be ready to make
a call. If you have configured you software's phonebook with some numbers
then just select one from there.If you would rather do it manually you can
use a @{ " Hayes " link HAYES} command. Type

ATDTxxxxxxxxxx

where the x's are the digits of the telephone number. Stuck for numbers? Ok,
here's a few to get you going:

/X\ostly Harmless (0705) 614-824
The Big Bang Burger Bar (081) 954-9967
Arkham BBS (071) 738-5596

There are many BBS's around so it is important for a BBS to attract
attention. Building a system round a theme or name can attract users - if
you called your BBS "Death Star" for example, people who liked Star Wars
would be more likely to call it.

Right. Once you have put the modem into action you will hear it dial the
number. If it gets an answer from another computer you'll hear a screeching
noise. Don't worry, this is just the modem and the modem at the other end
talking to each other to see how they should communicate. After a few
seconds you should see a 'CONNECT 2400' or similar message and then a
message telling you to press Escape. You are now on the @{ " BBS " link BBS}

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE BBS

  Bulletin Boards are by far the most common online services. There are
hundreds in Britain and thousands all over the world. A Bulletin Board is,
as the name suggests, like an electronic notice board. You can leave
messages there, pick them up and read messages left by others. In addition
to this  most BBS's have a file section which contains hundreds of Public
Domain (free) software.
  Most BBS's are run by comms enthusiasts for comms enthusiasts out of
people's bedrooms in their houses - they are not run for profit. Some boards
charge a fee to have access to a second line or to get other special
privileges, but most allow you to use them for nothing more than the cost of
a standard phone call.
The person who runs a Bulletin Board is called a Sysop (System Operator).
When you call a board you are connected to someone else's computer; a BBS
is just a piece of software.


After @{ " logging on " link LOGON} you will be presented with some text and then
a prompt to enter your name and secret password. If this is your first call
then you will be asked to enter some details. These are so the Sysop can
help identify you if you lose your password- don't worry your details will
not be passed on. You should always enter your real details.

So what can you do once you are on a BBS? Using a simple menu system you
will be able to make your way round several areas.

@{b}Files@{ub}

Most boards have a file section. There are usually many different 'areas'
with different topics such as art,music,text files,utilities and so on.
The files do not just magically appear though. It is up to the users of the
board to keep it alive. As well as taking files from the board @{ " (downloading) link PROTOCOLS}
it is important that you @{ " upload " link protocols} from time to time if you come across
a file the board does not have. Some BBS's give you an upload:download
ratio.

@{b}Games@{ub}

Moving on to another section, online games. These are here purely for fun.
They tend to be simple as complex graphics would take a long time to build
up over the phone. There are different types of games; from 'dungeons and
dragons' types to 'Tetris' clones.

@{b}Messages@{ub}

One of the main features of a BBS is its ability to carry messages. You can
chat with other users 'live' if there is more than one phone line or you can
leave messages that can be picked up by other users. There are normally many
different message areas. Mail can be private or it can by read by anyone.
For more information, consult the separate @{ " message " link MESSAGING} section.

Once you have finished your BBS session you have to log out. This means
selecting a special option on this board which will tell your modem you
have finished. You can't just hang up because this could crash the BBS
software and stop other users from going on until the sysop notices. If
something goes wrong and you have to hang up you should leave a note
explaining what happened to the Sysop.

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE MESSAGING

Most @{ " BBS's " link BBS} allow users to send messages to each other.
Using an international mail system however, you can talk to people all over
the world for the price of a local call.

@{b}The Fidonet@{ub}

  Fidonet was set up in 1984 by Tom Jennings, the sysop of a Bulletin
Board in America. He thought it would be nice if his users were able
to send messages not only between each other but between other users of
other boards as well. The idea was that "Fido" would pack all the
messages from his board that were for other boards, call the other
boards and deliver them. Within a year, 150 boards were part of the
system. Today there are well over 10,000 Fido nodes. The Fido @{ " structure " link STRUCTURE}
is quite complex consisting of various nodes and zones. The system still
works on the same principal - messages for users of other boards are
packed and sent on to the next where if a user who has a message is
found the message will be delivered to  that user and so on round the
globe. Messages belong to special topic areas where different subjects
are discussed. There are hundreds of topics. To give an idea of the
diversity, I have listed some below.

Music, the paranormal, astronomy, surrealism, cookery, genealogy , Dr
Who tv series, comms, satellite television, scouting, word processing,
games, air pilots, the arts, broadcasting, business advice, grand prix
racing, electronics.

  As you can see, there are a wide variety of topics to discuss. To
enter a discussion area, all you have to do is call a Bulletin Board
System that supports Fidonet, and read some message or you can enter a
new one. When you call back, you can read your replies and send more
messages. This is the simplest method of receiving and sending mail.
  Once they get used to the system, many people get hold of a piece of
software known as an OLR - an @{ " Offline Mail Reader " link OLR}. This system allows
you to download all the messages in your chosen areas and read and
reply to messages offline . Mail is downloaded in an archive
containing all the necessary data and your replies are also archived
and when you call the BBS again you @{ " upload " link PROTOCOLS} your replies and
@{ " download " link PROTOCOLS}  the new messages.
  I find that using an OLR is the easiest way of receiving and sending mail.
  Below is an example message to show how they are structured and how
what they involve.

----------------------------------------------------------------------

From:       Joe Bloggs
To:         Paul Moore
Subject:    Hard Disks
Date:       12-03-94 22:14

Hi @{b}Paul!@{ub}

@{b}Paul Moore@{ub} walks into a bar on @{b}<6 Mar 93>@{ub} and says to @{b}All@{ub}...

@{b} PM> Help! My hard disk has an error on it and I@{ub}

Get hold of DiskSalv, an excellent program available on most BBS's.
It will certainly clear up the error.

See Ya :-)

----
JOE *
----

... Double your HD space, double your computer speed: DELETE  WINDOWS!
--- GoldED 2.41
 * Origin: The Dustbin BBS (1:123/456.78)

----------------------------------------------------------------------

The first two lines identify the sender and receiver. The Fido
software will check if the receiver is a member of a board before
going onto the next one. These lines are also here for the users. The
subject is to remind the person receiving what the message is about,
which is handy if your receive and send many messages. A thread is a
set of messages all connected to the same subject. This is then
followed by the date which indicates when the original message was
sent as it can sometimes take a few days to go round from one part of
the world to the other. This message for example came from the USA and
took a few days to reach me.The main message follows next. Of
note in this section is the line containing PM> . This indicates that
it is a quote from my original message. It acts as another reminder to
me and it lets others know what we are talking about (the message is
from a public area, so anyone can read it). At the end of the message
you can see a set of characters, :-) . These are known as Smileys or
Emote icons. More about these later, but if you turn your head you
will probably see what they are. The line preceded by three dots is
known as a @{ " tagline. "link TAGLINES} It serves no real purpose other than to amuse.
Most mailing software contains an option to add a line from a text
file. The next line just indicates the name of the mailing software
used to write the letter. The last line in the message is the name of
the BBS the message originated on and its address. The address is
similar to the Internet address idea outlined earlier. The first
number in the line indicates the area of the world the message
originated in. This message originated in America which is area 1.
Europe is area 2 and Australasia is area 3.

  If you use Fido mail a lot, you can be come a Fido point. This is a
sub-point on the Sysop of your boards' Fido connection. You are given
your own unique address, so mail will come straight to your point,
rather than just onto the board. Using special software you can by-
pass all the usual login procedures and get your mail straight away.
Points can also make file requests allowing them to receive files
without wading through the menus of a board.Software such as Spot
and Trapdoor are widely used by Amiga Comms fans.

It isn't just ordinary users who are connected to the 'net. If you
wish to leave a message for US President Bill Clinton, you can leave
it be email. The President, Vice President and many US senators all
have Internet and Fidonet addresses.

It is also possible for you to send mail and receive mail between 
networks using the @{ " Fido <> Internet link " link NETLINKS}

If you have anything at all to do with computing, you will have met the
many abbreviations that are used for everything. You will meet some of
these in comms as well as some strange signs and you can have a closer
look at what these mean below.

@{ " TLA's    " link TLAS}
@{ " Smiley's " link SMILEYS}

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE TLAS

TLA's

  TLA stands for Three Letter Acronym. TLA's are used to abbreviate
messages and minimise time spent online as well as clarifying meaning.
Most TLA's are composed of more than three letters for some reason!
When you first read messages you will see these crop up often and
after a while you realise what they mean. Here are a few I have seen
in messages and what they mean:

BTW     - By The Way
FAQ     - Frequently Asked Question
IMO     - In My Opinion
FWIW    - For What It's Worth
IMHO    - In My Humble Opinion
ISTR    - I Seem To Recall
NALOPKT - Not A Lot Of People Know That
OTOH    - On The Other Hand
ROFL    - Rolls On Floor Laughing
RTFM    - Read The Friendly Manual
TIA     - Thanks In Advance
TPTB    - The Powers That Be

@{ " Return to menu       "  link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE SMILEYS

@{b}The Smiley Code@{ub}

  One problem that you sometimes have when sending messages that you
do not have when you are on the phone is getting emotions across;
people can take the meaning of your letter wrongly. For example if a
message said "You're a complete fool", the message could mean exactly
what it says or it could just be a tongue-in-cheek statement. To get
round this, a code was constructed by users known as the Smiley code
or Emote icons. These are used in messages to show that the writer is
laughing, crying or whatever. I've collected some common ones below.
To see what they are, you should turn your head or the paper round.


:-) Basic smiley. User is being humorous.

:-( Unhappy. User isn't pleased about something.

;-) Winking smiley. Message should not be taken seriously!

%-) Drunk smiley. User is completely out of his/her skull.

:-/ Sceptical smiley.

:-& Tongue tied. User can't speak about something or is lost for words.

:-# Gagged smiley. User is trying to keep quiet about something.

.-) User is keeping an eye out for something!

8-) Boggle eyed smiley.

:-D Laughing smiley.

:-)))) Extremely happy smiley.

:-(((( Extremely unhappy smiley.

B-) Glasses smiley.

:-O Shocked smiley.

:-| Miffed/Annoyed smiley.

:^( Nose out of joint smiley. Either happy or unhappy.

:-P Sticking out tongue smiley.


@{ " Return to menu      " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE HARDWARE


  Communication means the transfer of information over a distance
whether it is your voice over the telephone or letters exchanged by
people in different countries. In a computing environment anything
from personal messages to large programs can be transferred between
two computers. The normal method of transmission is over the standard
telephone line as used for voice communications. The telephone line
is not really suitable for this, though as some lines are not of a
very high quality which can cause the corruption of data. Fortunately
this is being improved as digital exchanges are being installed in
many countries, replacing the old mechanical systems that could cause
corruption as the mechanical clicking as people dialled numbers was
enough to degrade signals on nearby lines.

@{b}Hardware@{ub}

  Another problem with the standard telephone network is the way it
works means that it is unsuitable for computer data transmission. A
device to convert data to a form that can be transmitted down a line
and then converted back into a form the computer can understand is
required. This device is known as a Modem.
  A Modem (MODulator DEModulator)  transmits data using the @{ " serial " link SERIAL}
method of transfer, where one bit of data at a time is passed down
the wire, one after the other. This allows the use of the standard
telephone line. Another possible method is parallel transfer, as
used in most printers, where several bits are transmitted at once
down separate lines. This method is not common as it is costly ;
separate lines, receivers and transmitters are required for each bit
and each bit arrives at different times, causing the data to skew or
corrupt.
  The serial port on a computer is sometimes referred to as the RS232
port [RS423 on some machines]. When you dial  another computer one of
the modems tries to determine the transfer method by listening to the
noise made on the carrier. When it recognises the signal it switched
to the same mode as the other modem so both modems can 'talk' to each
other.
  The RS232 serial port was supposed to be a communication standard,
but as with many other things  (Beta / VHS in video, 3.5" or 5.25"
disks etc.) different manufacturers decided on different ports. A
true RS232 port is a 25-pin, but IBM decided to use a 9-pin for their
PC computers, Acorn thought the RS423 5-pin better and Apple use
their own type of connectors.
   When modems connect up, the most important thing they need to know
is the speed of transfer, or the Baud rate as it is known as. Baud
rate is the number of Bits transmitted per second. The higher the
baud rate, the faster the modem. Baud rates are continually
increasing - ten years ago, 1200 baud would be the fastest speed
available, with 300 baud considered fairly usable. Today 2400 is the
absolute minimum for reasonable communication, with 9600, 14400 and
16800 baud modems becoming more common. You will sometimes see modems
speeds referred to as @{" Vxx "link SPEEDS} where xx is a number.
   V23 differs from other baud rates as it is known as a split rate.
Data flows in one direction at 1200 baud and the other at 75 baud.
This method was used by British Telecom's PRESTEL service, which is
changing hands at the moment and will become 'New Prestel' apparently.
  Once the correct  cable  and  transfer  rate  are  selected, it is
important to ensure that the serial  port  is  set to receive and send
data in the same format as the other end. This takes the form of four
main items : data word size, parity, duplex and stop bits.

@{ " Data Word Size  " link DWS}
@{ " Parity Checking " link PARITY}
@{ " Duplex          " link DUPLEX}
@{ " Stop Bits       " link STOPBITS}


@{b}Noise on the line@{ub}

The main disadvantage of the phone line is that line noise can corrupt
data, particularly at high speeds.  Line  noise can be caused by many
things, including   noisy   mechanical  switching   equipment,   or
interference from adjacent lines. Line noise can be inconvenient if
you are looking around a service and words become corrupted, or a
major problem if you are trying to receive or send a file. At high
speeds, more data will become corrupted as the more data will be in
the process of transfer when the noise occurs.
  To solve this problem, and to quicken and standardise transfer, data
@{ " protocols " link PROTOCOLS}  such as Xmodem or Kermit have been developed.
  Some modems now come with built in error correcting. MNP is the most
common method used. There are different levels of error correction,
but MNP-5 is common in new modems. MNP-5 also compresses data whilst
transmitting, which can cut down on transfer times. Plain @{ " ASCII " link ASCII} text
compresses well, but many programs are already compressed with common
archivers such as ZIP,LHA or ARC, and MNP-5 can actually slow down the
rate of transfer in such cases. Some transfer protocols do not like
MNP correction either. Methods such as Ymodem-g are specially written
to leave correction to MNP.

The standard command set for modems is the @{ " Hayes " link HAYES} command set.


@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE DWS

@{b}Data Word Size@{ub}

Most Bulletin Boards and Online services use either 7 or 8-bit words.
An @{ " ASCII " link ASCII} text character consists  of  7-bits  as  this  is all that is
required to produce the standard character  set.  If you wish to use
characters in the extended set,  such  as  the  pound sign, you will
need to use 8-bits. The word  size  you use will be predetermined by
the system you are calling ; Prestel (which has changed hands) used 7-
bits for example, whilst most Bulletin Board Systems use 8 bits.

@{ " Serial Transmission " link SERIAL}
@{ " Return to Menu      " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE PARITY

@{b}Parity Checking@{ub}

Parity Checking is a simple form of  error  checking. An extra bit is
transmitted with each character. With  even  parity, this bit is set
to make the total number of  1's  in  the  binary character even. For
example, the 7 bit @{ " ASCII " link ASCII} code  for  "C" is 1000011. With even parity
the code becomes  11000011  (parity  bit  comes  first). The receiving
device checks the number of 1's. If  it is not even then an error has
been made. This method does not trap multiple errors which can cancel
each other out. Odd parity works in a similar way, except the number
of ones is set to be odd.

@{ " Serial Transmission " link SERIAL}
@{ " Return to Menu      " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE DUPLEX

@{b}Duplex@{ub}

Full Duplex is when data is transmitted in two directions
simultaneously. With Half-Duplex data is transmitted in both
directions, but only one at a time. Simplex involves the transmission
of data in one direction only. Half-Duplex is the norm for comms
today.

@{ " Serial Transmission " link SERIAL}
@{ " Return to Menu      " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE STOPBITS

@{b}Stop Bits@{ub}

The number of stop bits is the  final setting. This is normally set to
1 stop bit. With old, slow modems 2 stop bits were sometimes used to
make sure at least one was received. Start and stop bits indicate the
start and end of a data word.

@{ " Serial Transmission " link SERIAL}
@{ " Return to Menu      " link MENU}
@endnode


@NODE SOFTWARE

@{b}Software@{ub}

  Once you have sorted out the hardware side of comms, you will need
to get hold of terminal emulation software. This software is your
window to the world of computer communications. From it you will make all
your calls. Communication packages allow you to configure your setup
as you wish. You can select the modem speed, stop bits, transfer
protocols etc. from this software.
  Luckily enough all the Amiga's best comms software is shareware- you
can get hold of it for nothing and if you like it you pay the author a
small fee.

Of course you will find all the latest versions of Terminal software on
your favourite BBS, but you will also need software in the first place
so you can call a board, so if you don't know any other Amiga owners with
comms software then you can get some from a good PD library. Try 17bit
software on (0924) 366982 (voice!).

The most popular comms packages for the Amiga are @{ " Ncomm " system "display Commsguide.001"} and @{ " Term " system "display Commsguide.002"}. Ncomm
is currently in version 3 and Term is available in version 3.4. Both are
excellent packages and both offer extensive Arexx @{ " macro " link MACROS} support. It is
worth getting hold of both if you can. Term is available in special
processor specific versions so make sure you get the right one. There are 
of course other superb packages such as Terminus.


@{b}Features of Terminal Software@{ub}

As you would expect, Comms packages can handle all the different settings
you require to get your modem to operate correctly.  data word size, parity,
duplex and stop bits should all be configurable. For more info on these,
you should try:

@{ " Data Word Size  " link DWS}
@{ " Parity Checking " link PARITY}
@{ " Duplex          " link DUPLEX}
@{ " Stop Bits       " link STOPBITS}

You should also find an option to set the character set. Most systems
use the standard IBM font and so it is best to select this. If you are
using a modem with a reasonable speed, you can use ANSI colour. Normally
if you are just reading text, the standard computer @{ "ASCII " link ASCII} text system
will be fine. Most systems decorate their menus, and using ANSI will
allow simple graphics onscreen.

There will be an option to set the transfer @{ " protocol " link PROTOCOLS} This is very
important for @{ " uploading/downloading " link PROTOCOLS}

Your terminal software will have a capture option. This can be used to save
everything you do online to disk. It is useful for capturing messages
(although an OLR is better, see @{ " messaging " link MESSAGING} for more).
It can also be used to help you familiarize yourself with the layout of
a BBS.

If your software has a phonebook you can store all the numbers that you
call, and calling them is a simple matter of selecting them from the
phonebook.

Once you have your software set up, it is time to @{ " logon " link LOGON} to a
@{ " BBS " link BBS}

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE PROTOCOLS

@{b}Protocols@{ub}


  All communications packages should be capable of uploading and
downloading data. When you upload, you transfer data from your
computer to the other computer you are connected to. When you download
you receive data from the host computer.

   Transfer Protocols have been developed to solve the problem of
transferring data between computers. These protocols are designed to
optimise transfer times with the least amount of error. One of the
most common protocols is Xmodem. This protocol is not very speedy but
is efficient. Currently the most used protocol is Zmodem which is both
fast and efficient. A new protocol, Jmodem has been released recently.
If software supports the XPR library, then when a new protocol is
released, it can be added to the library. This means there is no need
to update the whole program. There are other protocols such as Ymodem
and Kermit (yes, named after the frog!).

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE MACROS

  A useful feature to have in a comms package is macros. Macros are
scripts that carry out a task for the user. For example, you could
have a macro that dialled your favourite board, entered your name and
password, transferred all your Email to your computer and then hung up.

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE HAYES


The @{b}Hayes@{ub} Command set

  When modems were first designed there was no common set of commands
for dialling. Hayes modems became very popular, and gradually the
command set from these modems became the norm as companies began
adopting "Hayes Compatible" modem commands. The commands are
proprietary however so it is possible that Hayes could stop modem
manufacturers from using the set.
  The Hayes command set is used to tell the modem to ring up, hang up
and so on. The actual set is quite small, and so other modem
manufacturers have been extending the command set. There is no
standard for the extend sets that appear in some modems.
  When the modem is offline - it is not connected to another machine,
the modem constantly checks for a recognised code and then acts on it.
Once the modem is online, it stops checking for the commands (
otherwise it would act on every command received even if it was not
meant to be a command, but was just a part of  a text file ; if a text
file contained say "...that he.." the AT and H from that extract would
be seen by the modem as a signal to hang up! ) Instead, when it is
online it constantly checks for an escape sequence and guard time. The
escape sequence tells the modem that it is to check for commands
again. The default escape sequence is +++. A guard time is required to
ensure that the what the modem thinks is an escape sequence is not
just part of the text being received. There is a one second delay
before and after the sequence. Below are some common Hayes commands
and what they do. Most start with AT, which means ATtention.

@{b}ATD@{ub} - Tells the modem to dial. Followed by T for tone dial P for
Pulse dial and then the number.

@{b}ATA@{ub} - The modem goes online and emits a signal. This is used if an
incoming signal from another computer is expected after a ring.

@{b}ATH@{ub} - Tells the modem to hang up

@{b}ATZ@{ub} - Sets the modem to its defaults.

@{b}ATI@{ub} - Tells the modem to give information about its manufacture. It
may come up with a code or a model name.

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE SERVICES

@{b}CIX@{ub}

  The Compulink Information eXchange is  a commercial service. You pay
a fee to join and pay  for  your  time  online as well as the standard
telephone charge. CIX is basically a  Bulletin Board but it has almost
100 lines. Its main emphasis  is  on  conferencing  -  you can enter a
conference and discuss subjects with other users.
  Unlike normal boards, everything is  in  conferences. Files are also
stored within conferences.
  One recent addition to CIX is  @{ " Internet " link INTERNET} access. .Via  CIX
you  can get  into many thousands of computers all over the  world.  The
only charge  is the standard CIX charge.

@{b}Compuserve@{ub}

Another online service, a bit similar to CIX. It offers live conferencing
and @{ " messaging " link MESSAGING} and many other services such as
online shopping , news and many other services. It is a subscription
service.



@{b}Prestel@{ub}

Prestel was British Telecom's online service, which recently closed.
Once you had paid a subscription you would have access to message
areas and databases. It wass a Viewdata or Videotex system - allowing
simple graphics like the Teletext service you can get on your TV.
 Prestel subscribers now have access to the French Viewdata system, Teletel.
The downside to this of course is that you have to have at least a rudimentary
knowledge of French to negotiate your way around...
 Latest information indicates that Prestel will morph into 'New Prestel', under
new management.


@{b}Telecom Gold@{ub}

This is another commercial service. It  could be accessed via BT's
Prestel or via a PSS (Packet Switched Stream) @{ " Network " link NETWORKS}
which allows local call access and saves cost. It is mainly used for sending
private messages.

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode


@NODE INTERNET

@{b}The Internet@{ub}

  The Internet is the largest @{ " network " link NETWORKS}  in the world. The current
estimated number of connected sites is 800,000.There are several
different types of nodes or sites as they are referred to. The main
three types of sites are educational such as universities, commercial
sites owned by businesses and government sites.
  Access to one of these sites means that you can log onto any of the
other sites in the network that will allow you . Until quite recently
the only chance for the average user to access Internet was by working
for a company that was a site or being a student, as most universities
in the world are connected to Internet. It would be very expensive to
set up your own connection to the Internet. Now, however there are a
number of commercial companies that can provide access to this network
for a few pounds a month .

  Every user of the Internet is given a unique address. This address,
like a normal address tells other users who the user is and where they
come from. A typical address would appear in this form:

                    @{b}PaulM@Unix1.co.uk@{ub}

This may look confusing as first, but it is quite simple when broken
down.The first section gives the user's name. This is followed by the
name of the computer that the user can be found on. "co.uk" tells us
the type of organisation and the country the site is in."co" refers to
a commercial company. If the site was a university or college it would
have been "edu" and if it was a government site it would be "gov".The
"uk" section is obvious. The structure of the message is required as
there are such a large number of sites. Each site also has an IP
address in numerical form , eg 123@45.678.901. The numbers correspond
to the sections in the text structure as shown above.

  @{b}File transfers@{ub}

  The average user of the Internet will have access to many millions
of files across the world. FTP is the Internet's File Transfer
Protocol. If you have access to a site you can transfer files from
that site to your computer.
  You cannot just log on to any computer and do what you want
though.Many computers do offer what is known as 'Anonymous FTP'.
Anonymous FTP allows anyone who wishes to log on to use the computer
without having an account at the site. You can obtain a site list from
many BBS's so it is not a problem finding out the address of a site.
  Once you have logged on to a site it is easy to move about from
directory to directory to look for particular files. The host computer
usually runs on a large mainframe with the UNIX operating system so
users of MS-Dos,AmigaDos or other systems offering command lines will
be familiar with commands such as 'cd' for changing directories. If
you see a file you want you can use the 'get' command.

 @{b}Gophers@{ub}

  The Internet is huge so it can be very difficult to locate that
certain file that you want. To help users find what they are looking
for there is a database called Gopher which is basically a "go for
this, go for that" utility. Once you have located the file you want,
you can get the Gopher to send it to you.

  @{b}Usenet@{ub}

  A sub-network of the Internet is Usenet, which is the Internet's
mail system. There are hundreds of different subjects discussed,
divided into newsgroups. A newsgroup could be about politics, the
arts, the meaning of life or what was on the telly last night.It is
possible to send mail from the Internet to @{ " Fidonet " link MESSAGING} using
the @{" Fido <> Internet link " link NETLINKS}

  @{b}Wading in MUD@{ub}

  Many sites on the Internet contain online games. Most of these are
in the form of MUD's - Multi User Dungeons. These are text adventures
played online, most with 'Dungeons and Dragons' type scenarios. The
difference between playing this sort of game at home and playing it
online is that there could be another 50 people playing with you, in
real time.

  @{b}FAQs@{ub}

  A FAQ is a set of Frequently Asked Questions - common questions on a
subject that people ask. Many FAQs on anything from cooking to Star
Trek are available on the Internet.


  @{b}Cost Cutting@{ub}

  A major advantage of an Internet link is  that the apart from the
connection fee you will probably pay monthly, the cost of the phone
bill is only to the place your connection is located. For example if
you phone a company in London to connect to the Internet, you are only
paying to connect to London even if you use the Internet to connect to
a computer in Australia. A further feature of the Internet is Telnet
which allows you to establish a remote connection to Bulletin Boards
via Internet, saving you the cost of dialling directly, so you could
call a board in America for a fraction of the normal cost.

  @{b}Where can you connect?@{ub}

  There are currently many commercial services that will for a fee
allow you to connect to them and access the Internet. CIX, who I have
mentioned previously do not charge anything more than their standard
connection charge for their conferencing services. Other companies,
such as DIS (Demon Internet Services) charge a flat rate, say Ł10 per
month.


@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE NETWORKS

@{b}Networks@{ub}

  What is a network? A computer network is a number of computers [
sometimes peripheral devices also ] interconnected by a number of
transmission paths. Local Area Networks or LANs are computers linked
up over a short distance such as a room or building. WANs or Wide Area
Networks connect many computers together over a large distance such as
a country or even the world. I will be looking at WANs in this
chapter.
  The most common network is @{ " Internet " link INTERNET} but here
are a few other WANS.

@{b}Arpanet@{ub}

Arpanet, the Advanced Research Projects Agency Network, is the oldest
network in the world, and one of the largest. The idea for such a
network, connecting mainframes and terminals over a large area was
first thought of in the 1950's to protect the US military's ability to
communicate after a nuclear strike . In the late 1960's it was
established and eventually linked around 60,000 computers or nodes in
the United States and other areas of the world.

@{b}Janet@{ub}

Janet , the Joint Academic Network , joins UK universities together as
well as research councils and other companies . Janet is mainly used
for the transmission of Files (such as statistics) and electronic
mail.

@{b}Fidonet@{ub}

@{ " Fidonet " link MESSAGING} is a large network connecting many small Bulletin
Board Systems together.

@{ "Return to menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE DOCS

Once you have @{ " unarchived " link ARCHIVERS} your files you will find that
most contain a 'doc' file, a text or Amigaguide (this sort) of document that
gives you instructions on using your utility and information about shareware
fees etc.

If you double-click the file it should load, but there are many different
text readers out there and you will probably not have them all. So if you
get a message like " Can't load file Inst.Txt; C:Less Not found " then you
need to know about tooltypes.

Click once on the icon of the file you are trying to read. Now select
Information from the icon menu of your Workbench screen. This will produce
an icon information window. You can now change the default tool box so that
instead of the program you don't have it will look for one you do.

You should have a copy of More on your workbench disk, in either the C or
utilities drawer. This is Commodore's standard text viewer.

If you have Workbench 3 or above you will have the excellent Multiview
program in your Utilities drawer. This program can view Amigaguide documents
like this one and plain text, as well as pictures and sounds.

If you have not got Workbench 3 you will need a copy of Amigaguide in order
to be able to view Amigaguide documents. This is now freely distributable so
you'll find it on a BBS or in a PD library.

@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode

@NODE SERIAL

@{b}Serial Transmission@{ub}

TIME
INTERVAL_____________9___0___1___2___3___4___5___6___7___8___9___
NUMBER
                     1       1           1       1   1       1
             Mark  +---+   +---+       +---+   +---+---+   +---+
LINE               |   | 0 |   | 0   0 |   | 0 |       | 0 |   |
CONDITION    Space-+   +---+   +---+---+   +---+       +---+   +-

                   ^   ^
                   |   |
BINARY        STOP-+  START  1   0   0   1   0   1   1   0
DIGIT

   The first 0 is the start bit; then follows 7 bits of the actual
letter code (1001011); then the parity bit; then the final 1 is the
stop code.
   This is the letter 'K' being transmitted.Data transmission is usually
Synchronous or Asynchronus. Synchronous transmission involves the synchronising
of Data Transmission between sender and receiver. Data is transmitted in 
blocks. This does not involve the use of start and stop bits. Asynchronous
uses start and stop bits to allow transmission of data with varying time gaps.



@{ " Return to main Menu " link MENU}
@endnode

