@NODE GLOSSARY

@{b}Glossary of Terms@{ub}

@{b}Note@{ub}: Not everything in this list is mentioned in the main text, but
there are a few terms that you might come across, so I have included
them too.

ANSI - American National Standards Institute. Standard for on screen
graphics for Bulletin Boards

@{ " ARCHIVER " link ARCHIVERS}- Program that compresses data, egLHARC,ZIP,ZOO,ARC.

@{ " ASCII "link ASCII} - American Standard Code for Information Interchange. Standard
code for plain text characters on computers.

ASYNCHRONOUS - See @{ " Data Transmission " link SERIAL}


AT - Set of dialling commands (see @{ " HAYES " link HAYES})

BAUD - Measurement in bits per second of the speed of data transfer.See also
       @{ " Speeds " link SPEEDS}

@{ " BBS " link BBS}- Bulletin Board System

BIT - Binary Digit (0 or 1)

BELL - Common name for US Telephone service

BLUEWAVE - A mail compression format

@{ " BT " link COST} - British Telecom

BYTE - 8 bits, represents one data character.

@{ " CIX " link SERVICES} - Compulink Information eXchange. an online service.

@{ " COMMS " link INTRO}- Communications.Common name for the hobby of computer
communications.

@{ " DOWNLOAD " link PROTOCOLS}- Recieve file from a host

@{ " DUPLEX " link DUPLEX}- The way data is transmitted - either full (both ways at the
same time), half (both ways, one at a time).

@{ " EMAIL " link MESSAGING}- Electronic Mail

FAQ - Frequently Asked Question

@{ " FIDONET " link MESSAGING} - Worldwide Email system

FTP - File Transfer @{ " Protocol " link PROTOCOLS}

HACKER - either someone who knows about computers or a person who
breaks into computer systems.

HANDSHAKING - Hardware & Software rules for modems to communicate with
each other. Signals include wait and acknowledged.

@{ " HAYES " link HAYES}- Standard dialling command set used by most modems.

HOST - the remote computer you are calling

@{ " INTERNET " link INTERNET}- Global network

KERMIT - Transfer @{ " Protocol " link PROTOCOLS}

LAN - Local Area @{ " Network " link NETWORKS}

MACRO - Scripts which act as a shortcut for common commands

@{ " MERCURY " link COST}- BT's competitor in the UK

@{ " MODEM " link HARDWARE}- Modulator-Demodulator. Device used for converting digital
computer signals to analogue and vice-versa.

@{ " NETWORK " link NETWORKS}- A number of linked computers.

NEW PRESTEL - See Prestel

NODE - A computer on a @{ " network " link NETWORKS}

@{ " OLR " link OLR} - Offline Mail Reader. See also @{ " Messaging " link MESSAGING}

@{ " PARALLEL " link HARDWARE} - Transmission of many bits at one time

@{ " PARITY " link PARITY}- A form of error checking

PHRACK - Phreak/Hack . The Hacker's magazine

POINT - A computer on @{ " Fidonet " link MESSAGING}

@{ " PRESTEL " link SERVICES}- Viewdata service

@{ " PROTOCOL " link PROTOCOLS}- Set of rules

@{ " QWK " link OLR} - A mail compression format

@{ " RS232 " link HARDWARE}  Serial Port standard

SCSI - Small Computer Systems Interface. An interface standard for
connecting devices to a computer.

@{ " SERIAL "link SERIAL}- Serial Transmission is the transmission of one bit at a time,
using a line,receiver and transmitter.

@{ " START/STOP BITS " link STOPBITS} - Used to indicate beginning and end of a data word.

SYNCHRONOUS - See { " Data Transmission " link SERIAL}

TELETEL - French Viewdata service

TERMINAL - computer used for comms

@{ " TLA " link TLAS}- Three Letter Acronym

UNIX - An Operating System

VIEWDATA - Terminal services presented as pages using blocky graphics

VT102 - ANSI setting

X/Y/ZMODEM - Transfer @{ " Protocols " link PROTOCOLS}


@{ " Return to main menu " link MENU}
@endnode


@NODE SPEEDS

Some examples;

V21    = 300 baud
V22    = 1200 baud
V22BIS = 2400 baud
V23    = 1200/75 (Split rate- 1200bps receive,75bps send)
V32    = 9600 baud
V32BIS = 14400 baud
HST    = 14400 baud (different from V32BIS though)



