@NODE BIBLIOGRAPHY

Soooooo....Fed up with my boring scrawl are we?     :-)


Here are some comms related books and articles you can get hold of which
will hopefully help fill you in where I've left you empty..


@{b}Books@{ub}
-Normal printed ones, available in print somewhere......


"Approaching Zero" - Bryan Clough and Paul Mungo (faber and faber, 1992) 

An excellent insight into the world of hacking. Worth reading if you're into
comms, it contains a lot of interesting stuff.


"The Hacker's Handbook" - Hugo Cornwall (New Century Communications, 1985)

The definitive book on comms. First published in 1985, and then later 
issued in an edited form as " The New Hacker's Handbook "this book may be a 
bit tricky to track down. Not to worry, some kind soul has typed or OCR'd it
into computer form and it's available on some BBS's such as the Big Bang
Burger Bar (081)954-9967 



@{b}Online Articles@{ub}
-These are available from good BBS's or Internet sites

"Zen and the Art of the Internet" - Brendan P. Kehoe 

A guide to that confusingly large network.


" Big Dummy's guide to the Internet "

Published by the EFF, this guide is available in Amigaguide format for the
Amiga and is to be found on most BBS's. It's very big and it's very good. It
may turn up in printed form eventually.


"Crime and Puzzlement" - John Perry Barlow (June, 1990)

Another good insight to the world of hacking as experienced by John Perry
Barlow of the EFF.


"Comms for Beginners" - David Foster *

A superb guide to comms for beginners, it is a general overview and goes 
into a bit more technical detail than here. Maybe a bit PC biased, but good.
Available on most BBS's.


