@NODE NETLINKS

It is possible for you to send mail from Fidonet to Internet if you have 
netmail (private mail) access. You can ask your sysop for netmail access.

Here's how to do it:

On the To: line, put UUCP and when asked for the address put 2:25/25. On the
first line of text where you would normally star your message, put something
like "To: PaulM@Unix1.co.uk" or whatever the address of the person is. Here's
a quick example:

From    : Arthur Dent
To      : UUCP 2:25/25
Subject : Towels
------------------------------------------------------------------

To: FordPrefect@Guide.co.bj

...and then the message.

-------------------------------------------------------------------


To receive mail back the way, get the internet user to send it to 

Your.name@p0.fxxx.nxxx.z2.fidonet.org

where the xxx's are the address numbers of your BBS.


@endnode

@NODE ASCII

ASCII, the American Standard Code for Information Interchange is a standard
format for information exchange between computers and programs. ASCII 
involves the use of a code to represent each character in the alphabet,
for example the letter "A" is ASCII code 65 and a slash, "/" is ASCII code
47.

@endnode

@NODE OLR

If you're looking for a good Offline Mail Reader, two good choices are 
@{ " AmyBW " system "display commsguide.003"} and @{ " QBlue " system "display commsguide.004"}. AmyBW can cope with the Bluewave mail packing system 
whilst AQuick is good with the common QWK mail method. As with comms
packages, it is worth getting hold of them both (and some other ones if 
you see any) as they are just a download away. One thing to consider is 
that it can be quite tricky to set up such software using floppies, so if
you have a hard disk you'll find it a lot easier going.

@endnode

